text:
Norway isn't for everyone. I'm Greek who lives half the year in Bergen and half in Athens. Business isn't that hard to open, but complications often arise for reasons that are weird for most of the Europeans. (We wanted to open a 3rd restaurant with Greek-style sea food, since we already have 2 in Greece, but were told we can't use Greek imports to cook the food, it must all be Norwegian made. I didn't know there's Norwegian evoo or feta, but that's besides the point). They killed our enthusiasm from the start. They simply don't like foreigners. Any foreigners. But they sure love to sunbathe on the Mediterranean. 
  Apart from the imminent depression and mood swings newcomers usually face here, it isn't all that bad. It's expensive on purpose, like America. Buffed up salaries produce buffed up prices, to repel non-Norwegians. It's how it works.
  Alcohol is expensive, yeah, but the alcohol and drug culture here is off the charts. People make their own alcohol everywhere, and it's anything but safe to drink. Blame the legal Monopoly.
